A review for Bed of Snake by YellowNoteAnon

I had hopes for this story, I really did. The description was good, the world building was nice and immersive. Initially I felt it was building up to something good, improving with every chapter.

Then I read chapter 7, and I don't think I can recommend it anymore.

The biggest flaw is the two MC's, Clyde and Cherry. I hoped Clyde was manning up in the last chapter, and was growing a spine to stand up to Cherry's bullshit. But I felt that was undone at the end of this chapter, that he just accepts his situation he's in: being intimidated, threatened and stalked by the very viper that mugged him, and coerced him. He feels flat, that the world's just going by and he just flows with it, there's nothing consequential about his actions, or him as a character, or any reason to like or care for him.

Then there's Cherry. At the start, I felt she would start out flawed and would evolve as the story went on, perhaps having remorse for her actions, taking accountability, and wanting to change. But that hasn't manifested. Like Clyde, she feels static, which isn't necessarily a bad thing, static characters can be good. But I don't like her. She's sadistic, arrogant, pushy, manipulative and feels no remorse, or guilt, even hiring the faceless that nearly assaulted Clyde. I had some hope, until the end where Cherry threatened Clyde's life, and articulated why. I just can't like a character who would do that, or fathom why the relationship would grow from that point on.

People sometimes defend character's action with 'it's realistic' or 'how would you react in that situation?' But many writers forget, realistic doesn't equal fun to read, especially when characters make dumb decisions purely for the plot to happen.

I think it's saying something when I think the muton shop owner seems to be a more interesting story, and a likable character.

Recommended if you're into /adhg/, if not, look elsewhere.

The first thread that began continuity was in 2017, and exceedingly few of the people of that year remain. Were it not for a cadre of exceeding productive artists and writers I doubt the modern /hmofa/ would've been born. Some of these early members include STRONG, Armain, Alfa_Barf, Azhumier, Vuko, Sometingaboutsharks, and ComfyCreations, there were many others but theres were some of the most important, Azhumier particularly as he laid the foundation of this thread's organization. In 2018 new faces emerged, including some familiar faces like Oliver_Hart, myself, etc. In 2019 we lost most of the old guard , some remain of course, but few and those that do are familiar names. In 2021 mostly due to the lockdowns and an unprecedented wave of trolling, we hemorrhaged creators leading to creation of furchan which I'm not sure is used at all anymore. This nearly caused designated /hmofa/ artists to go extinct, Blokfort stopped really coming to the thread, as did Vuko, we lost many others too, Wetchop, Botantics, Thighlordash, and more. But in 2022 we regained more and emerging from the thinning came a fourth wave of creators

It debated how many "generations" of hmofa creators there are but those from the founding September of 2017 to May of 2018 are considered the founders, from May of 2018 through 2019 or 2020 is its own bloc while the whole of 2020-2023 may be considered separate. Either way this general has had one defining trait above all, perseverance. No matter who leaves hmofa continues.
